  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_5",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: compare two groups. The most common inferential question — is group A different from group B? Compare groups on 'auto' inspects each group for normality (Jarque-Bera) and equal variance and PICKS the test for you: a Welch t-test when both groups look roughly normal, a Mann-Whitney U (rank) test when they do not; it surfaces the choice and any assumption warnings so the decision is visible, not hidden. Read the output in order: (1) which test fired and why, (2) the p-value against your α, (3) the DIRECTION and size of the difference — the boxplot shows the medians, spread and any outliers, and the significance bar marks a detected difference. A significant p tells you the groups differ; the boxplot tells you by how much and whether it matters. Student (1908); Mann & Whitney (1947); Welch (1947).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
